Ensemble Performance is an official Department Ensemble, so students participating in this Samba Ensemble gain course credit. Students have the option to participate in a music department sponsored group for two consecutive semesters (i.e. one academic year). Other ensemble groups include University Orchestra, University Wind Ensemble, Choral Society, University Choir, Ancient Voices, Baroque and Recorder Ensemble, Chamber Music Society and Jazz Combo. &#8232;&#8232;

This class is described consistently as “simply great,” “a lot of fun,” engaging,” “awesome, and loud.” Students “look forward to the class every week” and noted that, “beginners are more than welcome.” The environment is “fun and friendly,” and students enjoyed the opportunity to “learn how to play a variety of different samba instruments.” Students described this class as among the “most interesting and enjoyable” Penn courses they have taken. The hands-on nature allowed students to broaden “musical horizons” significantly. They nonetheless expressed a desire for “the group [to] have set shows with the music department.” &#8232;

Professor Stevens is a “great and passionate instructor” who is “very skilled at what he does.” Students frequently reference the “great atmosphere” in class, and find the instructor supportive of the learning experience. They appreciated that Professor Stevens “pushes his students and keeps the course interesting.” &#8232;

No prior musical, sight-reading, or percussion experience is necessary, and all instruments are provided. This course must be taken for a letter grade (Pass/Fail registration option may not be utilized for this course). All Music majors are required to participate in one of the MUSC 007 groups for at least four semesters. An audition is required for this class.
